Sure, here is the C# code to sort an array using quicksort algorithm:

```c#
public static void QuickSort(int[] array, int left, int right)
{
    if (left < right)
    {
        // Choose the pivot element.
        int pivot = array[left];

        // Partition the array around the pivot element.
        int i = left + 1;
        int j = right;
        while (i <= j)
        {
            while (array[i] < pivot)
            {
                i++;
            }
            while (array[j] > pivot)
            {
                j--;
            }
            if (i <= j)
            {
                // Swap the elements at index i and index j.
                int temp = array[i];
                array[i] = array[j];
                array[j] = temp;
                i++;
                j--;
            }
        }

        // Recursively sort the left and right subarrays.
        QuickSort(array, left, j);
        QuickSort(array, i, right);
    }
}
```

This code works by recursively partitioning the array around a pivot element. The pivot element is chosen as the middle element of the array, but any element could be chosen. The array is then partitioned into two subarrays, one containing all elements less than or equal to the pivot, and the other containing all elements greater than the pivot. The left subarray is then recursively sorted, and the right subarray is then recursively sorted. This process continues until the entire array is sorted.

The quicksort algorithm is a divide-and-conquer algorithm, which means that it breaks down the problem of sorting an array into smaller and smaller problems until they are simple enough to be solved directly. This makes it a very efficient algorithm for sorting large arrays.

