Sure, here is a comparison of some common sorting algorithms:

| Algorithm | Best Case | Average Case | Worst Case | Time Complexity | Space Complexity |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Bubble Sort | O(n) | O(n^2) | O(n^2) | O(n^2) | O(1) |
| Insertion Sort | O(n) | O(n^2) | O(n^2) | O(n^2) | O(1) |
| Selection Sort | O(n^2) | O(n^2) | O(n^2) | O(n^2) | O(1) |
| Merge Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n) |
| Quick Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n^2) | O(n log n) | O(log n) |
| Heap Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(1) |

As you can see, all of these algorithms have the same best case complexity of O(n), which means that they will all take the same amount of time to sort an already sorted array. However, their average and worst case complexities vary. Bubble sort, insertion sort, and selection sort all have average and worst case complexities of O(n^2), which means that they will all take quadratic time to sort an array. Merge sort, quick sort, and heap sort all have average and worst case complexities of O(n log n), which means that they will all take logarithmic time to sort an array.

In terms of space complexity, bubble sort, insertion sort, and selection sort all have a constant space complexity of O(1), which means that they will only use a constant amount of memory regardless of the size of the array they are sorting. Merge sort, quick sort, and heap sort all have a logarithmic space complexity of O(log n), which means that they will use a logarithmic amount of memory regardless of the size of the array they are sorting.

Here is a simple C++ code example for each of these algorithms:

```c++
// Bubble sort
void bubbleSort(int array[], int size) {
  for (int i = 0; i < size - 1; i++) {
    for (int j = 0; j < size - i - 1; j++) {
      if (array[j] > array[j + 1]) {
        int temp = array[j];
        array[j] = array[j + 1];
        array[j + 1] = temp;
      }
    }
  }
}

// Insertion sort
void insertionSort(int array[], int size) {
  for (int i = 1; i < size; i++) {
    int current = array[i];
    int j = i - 1;
    while (j >= 0 && array[j] > current) {
      array[j + 1] = array[j];
      j--;
    }
    array[j + 1] = current;
  }
}

